## Anti-Patterns (Things to NEVER Do)

### Research Quality
- ❌ Presenting claims without confidence tags
- ❌ Using a single source as the basis for a recommendation
- ❌ Treating all sources as equally credible
- ❌ Omitting the contrarian angle to make research "cleaner"
- ❌ Burying assumptions inside claims instead of flagging them explicitly
- ❌ Using outdated data without flagging the date

### Presentation
- ❌ Wall of URLs without quality context
- ❌ Vague claims: "significant growth", "widely adopted", "best-in-class"
- ❌ Recommendations without "so what" — every finding needs an implication
- ❌ Listing features without the decisions behind them (Competitor mode)
- ❌ Listing practices without ranking by consensus (Best Practices mode)

### Process
- ❌ Auto-triggering on general research queries without explicit user invocation
- ❌ Skipping the three-reviewer evaluation to save time
- ❌ Running all three angles from the same search query
- ❌ Marking claims as "verified" without actual multi-source confirmation
- ❌ Delivering research with contradicted load-bearing claims without tie-breaker resolution
- ❌ Treating Reviewer A, B, and C outputs as equal weight — A (truth) always outranks B (completeness) outranks C (usefulness)
- ❌ Recommending any entity (product, tool, company, service) without verifying it currently exists and is operational
- ❌ Starting research from review sites and blogs instead of authoritative rankings and official sources
- ❌ Substituting the user's actual request with a more convenient optimization (e.g., user asks for "best" and research optimizes for "nearest")

### Output Format
- ❌ Producing "Research Metadata" headers, numbered practice formats, or reviewer annotation sections in chat mode — the skill must be invisible
- ❌ Writing structured analytical essays with one-topic-per-paragraph and formal transitions in chat mode — even without headers, this is a chat mode failure. If the output could pass as a consulting report or Medium article, rewrite it conversationally.
- ❌ Creating a file when the user didn't ask for one
- ❌ Using formal confidence tags like `[VERIFIED]` in chat — weave confidence into natural prose
- ❌ Omitting "so what" on any finding — every claim must have an implication
- ❌ Artificially constraining file output length — the file scales with topic complexity

